  "narrative": "<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Short impact summary</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">Published in 2024 by Peter Lang Verlag, <em>Streaming the Formula 1 Rivalry</em> by Raymond Boyle and Richard Haynes has accumulated 8 citations since its release, placing it in the top 1 percent of comparable outputs by citation velocity. The book is available open access and has already drawn the attention of researchers across media studies, sport sociology, and sports marketing on at least three continents.</p>\n\n<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Full narrative</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">Boyle and Haynes situate Formula 1 at the intersection of streaming platforms, media economics, and sporting spectacle, examining how digital distribution has reshaped one of the world's most commercially intensive sports properties. The volume appears as part of Peter Lang's <em>Communication, Sport, and Society</em> series, which encompasses a sustained body of work on sport media across topics ranging from sports journalism to fan culture and gender politics. Within that company, this title addresses a distinctly contemporary question: how the rivalry logic of F1\u2014between drivers, teams, and commercial entities\u2014is amplified and transformed by the streaming era.</p>\n\n<p class=\"story-text\">The book's citation trajectory signals genuine scholarly uptake that has accelerated over time. A single citation arrived in 2024, followed by three in 2025 and four already recorded for 2026, suggesting growing relevance rather than a flash of early attention. Citing works appear across a range of reputable peer-reviewed venues including <em>Media Culture &amp; Society</em>, <em>Leisure Studies</em>, <em>Convergence</em>, the <em>International Review for the Sociology of Sport</em>, and the <em>International Journal of Sports Marketing and Sponsorship</em>. This spread across media studies, sport sociology, and marketing scholarship reflects the book's genuinely interdisciplinary purchase. Thematically, citing authors engage with advertising and commercial culture, fandom, digital spectacle, and the sport-media-business nexus\u2014territory the book evidently helps to frame. Geographically, those citing works originate from Australia, the United Kingdom, Italy, Belgium, France, Germany, New Zealand, Russia, and the United States, indicating an international readership that extends well beyond the authors' home context.</p>\n\n<p class=\"story-text\">Several citing works merit note for their thematic proximity. Research on F1 fans' responses to format changes, on the symbolic capital generated by the Netflix series <em>Drive to Survive</em>, and on alcohol-free branding strategies in Formula 1 all draw on the book's analytical framework. A book chapter examining F1's expansion into the Middle East through a sportswashing lens similarly positions Boyle and Haynes as foundational reference points for critical scholarship on the sport. This clustering of F1-specific citations suggests the work is functioning as a field-anchoring text for an emerging subfield concerned with motor sport, media, and commercial power.</p>\n\n<p class=\"story-text\">Beyond formal citation, the book's reach extends to professional and educational settings. A webinar hosted by the Facultat d'Empresa i Comunicaci\u00f3 at the University of Vic featured discussion of the book under the title \"F1 and the Media,\" pointing to adoption in higher education contexts focused on sport communication and media business. The book's green open-access status removes cost barriers to that kind of pedagogical use. Commercial availability through major retail platforms further broadens its visibility beyond academic library holdings. Together, these signals\u2014a strong citation percentile, disciplinary breadth among citing authors, international spread, and documented teaching engagement\u2014mark <em>Streaming the Formula 1 Rivalry</em> as an early-stage but notably active contribution to the scholarly literature on sport, media, and digital transformation.</p>",
